 this framework to advance their particular interests. Yahaya explains why Arab minorities in the region helped to fuel the entrenchment of European colonial legalities: their itinerant lives made institutional records necessary. Securely stored in centralized repositories, such records could be presented as evidence in legal disputes. To ensure accountability down the line, Arab merchants valued notarial attestation land deeds, inheritance papers, and marriage certificates by recognized state officials. Colonial subjects continually played one jurisdiction against another, sometimes preferring that colonial legal authorities administer Islamic law—even against fellow Muslims.Fluid Jurisdictions draws on lively material from multiple international archives to demonstrate the interplay between colonial projections of order and their realities, Arab navigation of legally plural systems in Southeast Asia and beyond, and the fraught and deeply human struggles that played out between family, religious, contract, and commercial legal orders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArabsxLegal status, laws, etczIndonesia. 0aArabsxLegal status, laws, etczStraits Settlements. 0aArabsxLegal status, laws, etc.zIndonesia. 0aArabsxLegal status, laws, etc.zStraits Settlements. 0aImperialismxSocial aspectszSoutheast AsiaxHistory. 4aIslamic Religion & Studies. 4aLegal History & Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Asian.2bisacsh  aSoutheast Asia, Islamic Law, British Empire, Dutch Empire, Islam, colonialism, Netherlands Indies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 20